  "original_title": "\u0db1\u0dcf\u0dc3\u0dcf \u0dc4\u0dd2 \u0db4\u0dc5\u0db8\u0dd4 \u0db4\u0dd6\u0dbb\u0dca\u0dab-\u0dc0\u0dbb\u0dca\u0dab \u0d85\u0db7\u0dca\u200d\u0dba\u0dc0\u0d9a\u0dcf\u0dc1 \u0da1\u0dcf\u0dba\u0dcf\u0dbb\u0dd6\u0db4\u0dba",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "NASA's first full-color space photo",
      "author": "unknown",
      "body_lines": [
        "The James Webb Space Telescope, also known as JWST or Webb, has released the first-ever full-color image.",
        "This photo was taken after the newly launched space telescope went through a six-month process of unfolding all its components, aligning its mirrors and calibrating its instruments.",
        "Taken by Webb's Near-Infrared Camera, the image, dubbed Webb's First Deep Field, captured thousands of galaxies in great detail.",
        "The field in question is a composite of images at different wavelengths showing the galaxy cluster SMACS 0723, which appeared 4.6 billion years ago, according to NASA."
      ],
